    "reasoning": "First, compute p_{10}, the stopping probability when initially there are 10 white and 10 black socks. Under the interpretation that Roger stops only after drawing at least one sock and when the remaining socks are equal, we start at (10,10). After the first draw, the state becomes (9,10) or (10,9) with equal probability. For an unequal state (w,b), the probability of eventually hitting equality before empty is 2*min(w,b)/(w+b). For (9,10), this is 18/19; same for (10,9). Thus, p_{10} = (1/2)*(18/19) + (1/2)*(18/19) = 18/19.

Next, the number of frogs in the pool is p_{10} + 38324/19 = 18/19 + 38324/19 = 38342/19 = 2018. There is 1 frog on the shore, so total frogs N = 2019.

Model the frog process as a Markov chain where the state is the number of frogs in the pool. Transitions: from state i, with probability i/N, move to i-1; with probability (N-i)/N, move to i+1. We want the expected time to hit state N starting from state N-1. Let E_i be this expected time. For small N, we find E_{N-1} = 2^N - 1 (e.g., N=2 gives 3, N=3 gives 7, N=4 gives 15, N=5 gives 31). Thus, for N=2019, the expected time is 2^2019 - 1.",
